snippet.textDisplay:
After living in Spain for a year, moving from the US
, it is unavoidable just how horrible health care is in the USA. In Spain, while things are far from perfect with the universal health care, if you are sick you get treated, and yes it can take time if what you are getting treatment for is not urgent. If you don’t want to deal with the public system, private insurance costs for a year what we were paying for a month in the USA. If you are very sick, you get treatment right with the public healthcare. Prescriptions are subsidized, they cost a tiny fraction of what they cost in the US. It isn’t perfect, but it is so much better than what we had to deal with in the States. Taxes are high here compared to what we were paying, but I would rather have a population that is healthier and happier than more money in my pocket. When I explain healthcare in the US to people here, they really cannot believe it (homelessness also, we were in Seattle and it was out of control). From abroad I continue to support Bernie Sanders, he is really the only hope I can see for my home country.

snippet.textDisplay:
Why do I feel like the countries manufacturing these medications outside America is being portrayed like an illegal drug dealer?
America has different laws and patent-laws than these countries. In my country, if Lab A invented a drug for, lets say, fever and patented it; they'll have the sole right to sell the drug for a couple of years but once this patent expires Lab A is required by law to sell it's formula to other laboratories to produce the same medication. By doing so, the market has now multiple "brands" of a medication with similar formula, it will not only make the price go lower but the supply higher.
